Why I say that those 2 white lines, the nails have to be in between them to not void the warranty of the shingle. That's the manufacturer's requirement. There's no if ams or butts about it. commentText: Ex-truck driver here.   I drove Cents Per Mile, owner operator and lease operator. OTR.   It not very profitable.   -owner operator. If you buy a brand new truck, your expenses go towards the truck payment, trailer payment (which is another expense), insurance for both truck and trailer, insurance for the loads, fuel for both truck and trailer, IFTA,  Tolls (east coast tolls are absurdly expensive) . Plus,  repair schedules. Also, depends highly on what the market offers and other factors. Sure, you can earn 350k - 450k gross per year. BUT, with all of those expenses  you will net under 60k per year. And then you're taxed on personal income.  If you buy USED equipment, the same as above applies, except now there are major pending issues, repairs, and preventive  maintenance. Your equipment will become a risk factor. -Cpm (cent per mile) you can earn 50-75 cents per mile, but most  if not all, companies have you running from zipcode to zipcode basis instead of per mile. You have no control on maintenance and no control on basically anything. And then escrow gets removed, also, personal tax at 33%.  -lease operator is almost a hybrid of both owner and CPM, just depending of the clauses being signed for at the beginning of your contract agreements.  The only and best way to make good money is if you own a company and have everyone else work for you,  take no executive decisions with 200+ trucks, have your own shop, have your own insurance firm and have PRISTINE, loyal and fully dedicated drivers under your belt. But, that is just a dream.

Still with that company but now a floater (thinking about traveling nurse but as a truck driver for other local yards) and expecting to make 140k this year. I work 4 weeks and 1 week home, the one week home I still get paid. Sometimes you just gotta keep looking at the job listings other times you have to know somebody to get you in. For most local jobs though I would say expect to make around 60-80k and if hauling hazmat maybe up to 100k or decently more depending on area. Still better than a lot and more than enough to live on depending on your area.  You could also work for a mega carrier (Big Fleet companies like Swift, CR England, knight, etc.) and eventually become a trainer. I‚Äôve heard lots of numbers for this but never personally done it so can‚Äôt vouch but have heard they can make anywhere from 120-180k a year depending how many trainees they want.

commentText: A field many are not familiar with is Nondestructive testing (NDT).   In this, you do inspections, typically looking for cracks, corrosion, and erosion of metal in critical systems and structures.  It has applications in aviation, manufacturing, repair, shipping, and industrial fields.   Lots of variety in the day to day operations keeps it from getting too repetitive.  You can also get certified to inspect welds.  Lol, most welders I have met want to get into NDT.   Smart kids who can do a little math can work up to 6 figures in around 5 years.  Demand for the job is high.    For those interested in joining the military (especially the Air Force), this is a great field to get into as you can get all the training and experience while you serve.

commentText: Good video Jeff, I would say that particularly as related to the building trades, there are two factors that dramatically affect the work.  Those two distinctions would be 1) new construction vs. remodel/service work 2) commercial vs. residential.  A residential service plumber is a very different career than a commercial new construction plumber/pipe fitter.  The first involves backed up drains, leaky faucets, bath remodels, etc. which is a great job, but it is not the same experience that a new construction plumber working on new hospital or data center will have.  This would equally apply to most other building trades.  I think the generalization of trades across these factors also waters down the salary information.  With that said, having spent nearly 40 years in commercial construction, I would recommend anyone looking for a new career who is interested in "making things" and seeing the result of their work daily look at commercial building trades.  Electrician, plumber, sheet metal, carpentry (finish & rough), pipe fitter, fire sprinkler, fire alarm/low voltage, flooring, tile, terrazzo, waterproofing, metal studs/drywall, concrete, elevators, masonry, etc.  They all have something to offer and the diversity in work and conditions should allow you to fit into one you enjoy.  Also, most skills learned in any of these trades can apply to any of the other so if you don't like the first one you try, find other to experience.

So I stay busy 6 days per week, work in the field about 5 hours per day, home for lunch every day, pick my own hours, and still average $75,000 per year! I chose not to install whole doors, so this saves body wear and tear(I‚Äôm 48). For guys like me who also install doors, it is not unheard of to make over $100,000 per year! The key is picking a very populated area, an in demand trade, and a ton of wealthy citizens.

commentText: I keep seeing Gators fans saying things like, "Maybe he won't be so bad after all," and, "He's kind of winning me over," and, "The more I learn about him, the better I like him."   Yeah. That's how that's _supposed_ to work but my fellow Gators fans are irrational and have zero chill. Y'all called for him to be fired before he was even announced and called him things like Napier 2.0 (don't even get me started on that one). I said I'll wait and see how the presser goes, who he hires, and how recruiting goes. Guess what? It went as well as it could have gone. He nailed the intro presser. He hired the best possible coordinators any team could hire. Now he's recruiting like crazy and has kept the class together. So let's see what else happens before we make another snap judgement. I'm still waiting to see how media days and the camps go but I am excited about all the good news.  Will Gators fans learn from this? No. The moment he does something trivial like spill his coffee, Gators fans will run him out of town.

commentText: Yeah Republic services the one that's out of Hudson Florida there, they are a garbage collection business. They've had to close up because they've lost major county accounts I guess, at least here in Hernando county. The counties were drawing up contracts for new waste disposal and Republic came up a little bit more money than the other service that put their bid in, so that's probably why they've had to close that down.  The economy here is interesting to say the least. If you're coming from another state and you're used to getting paid more money, you will get paid a lot less here but you'll be paying more for housing and rent. The governor just announced today that they are going to put a referendum on November 2026 ballot. He's trying to do away with property taxes. Florida would be the first state to not have any property tax. In a good economy, this would probably would work for us, but it's a little early to say that they will be able to get money from other places to cover services.  I think if they can make it work it will cause a major housing boom down here. There are houses being built and apartment buildings being built right and left, but nobody's moving into them yet. Our housing market is teetering as homeowners insurance is so incredibly expensive in some areas. And for everyone that's noticed that our hurricane season has been slow, (we don't use the Q word) that is absolutely not normal! Lucky, but not normal! commentText: As an SEC Alumnus out here in Arizona (my home state), I would not underestimate Jedd Fisch's motivation to leave Seattle.  He is grossly out-of-place in that ultra-liberal, far left "woke" environment compared to SEC country (more conservative).  Jedd was trained by Spurrier at his Alma Mater, Florida.  Here in AZ, he did the unthinkable by turning the Wildcats into an SEC caliber of team two years ago. I was at Tempe when U of A routed ASU.  But U of A had administration problems and Fisch left for Washington.  But he could leave again as I understand he and his family are not happy in Seattle.  Honestly, as a Gator I would prefer Jedd over Lane.  I think Kiffin should stay at Ole Miss.  Jedd could be hired with a bargain and probably be just as good in bringing the Gators back.  I saw his work here in Arizona.   As for SEC football, that Ole Miss-Florida game at Gainesville ten years ago was the most intense I had ever seen from a home crowd.  I was an undergraduate at Notre Dame and attended the last championship game for ND in 1989 at the Fiesta Bowl.  That Ole Miss-Florida game had far more energy and loudness by far.

commentText: 14 years Kiffin has been a head coach in college. He's been at Tennessee, USC, FAU and Ole Miss. In those 14 years, his teams have only finished the season ranked in the Top 25 on 4 occasions. This year will make 5.  In his 11 years at the Power-4 level as a HC, he has never won a Natty or made it to a National Title game. He has never won a Conference Title or even made it to a Conference Title game. He won't this year either.  I've never in my life seen fans and now AD's and school president's go completely goofy over someone who hasn't won anything as a HC at a P-4 program. His biggest win ever is against Georgia in 2024. It was just a regular season game. Everybody hated his ass for 2 decades and now Florida and LSU are supposedly offering $15 million per year to land him. üòÇ He literally has one 11 win season coming into this year.   Most coaches that get courted by other schools like Kiffin has, those coaches have an entire wing of their house dedicated just to all their trophies. Yet here is Lane Kiffin and his trophies could all fit in a medicine cabinet with room to spare. Well, maybe he could fill a broom closet. üòÇ
